European Inflation Sliding into Food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is primarily due to skyrocketing food price growth.
The increase in prices in the month of November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, registering - after 2.6 percent of the month of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Union Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts gave a likely 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the American, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, together with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to, two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: “we have to negotiate” on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, registered in Germany, broke the 12-year record; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of soaring food and energy prices.
Wheat forward quotations increased by 88 percent and soya prices also reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching already last month black gold almost 100 dollars a barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while in 2009 it will already decrease to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December the support of the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while the Gallup never before experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of the socialists.
The difference in the case of the confident voters of the parties - due to the greater firmness of the voters of the opposition - would mean a support of more than two-thirds (71%) against the support of one-fifth for the socialists (20%).
According to the poll, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach even the limit necessary to have any parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the secure voters there are one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low point – the proportion of those who judged the country’s economic situation especially bad has never been higher, with 41 percent believing the situation to be quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as the next year is concerned, the majority of the population is counting on the deterioration of the situation and only a tenth expect an improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those polled, higher than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the president of the government performs rather poorly than well in his duties.
13 percent of those consulted trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány a lot, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of those consulted.
Fifty-four percent of the population does not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks that it is possible to control the discontent experienced in front of the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the riots in October last year, 35 percent thought it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, today this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believes that holding new elections is the only solution.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question on participation answered that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said that they are likely to participate.
By way of comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" only 55 percent of the population would surely participate and another 15 percent believe their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt of the result of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of study fees, 79 percent of the medical consultation service and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the confident participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of study rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
They maintained the average price level increase of 16 percent in the hypermarkets of the golden trading triangle of Budaers, with the difference that this year the VAT has not been increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the golden commercial triangle of Budaers the usual Christmas basket of the Napi newspaper, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth well above one thousand HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already "fired" in December last year, so there was not a drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below nine thousand HUF, today they cannot even do it for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded with a minimum of 91 HUF the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(In 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the previous year’s level, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Statistical Office, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with a two-liter redeemable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
All in all, Napi Auchan’s basket was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to Christmas prices last year, Cora increased by 15 percent, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent the prices listed in the Napi basket.
Comparing the values of last year’s most expensive basket with that of this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive has been 21 percent.
The mean growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so that last year’s Christmas in prices was felt the VAT increase.
Precisely this process was the one that destroyed trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the change in prices on consumption.
(If the merchant misplans the speed of a product’s circulation, he may lose a significant profit on the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was superior with 1720 HUF to the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
No such extremes occurred this year, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of basic consumer items grew more than 30 percent.
(However this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some staple foods recorded in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
So, for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of the egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, there was only a 10 percent increase in prices in the worst case.
By all indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic increase in prices even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain about the golden trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our collected experiences, the majority of consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking preserved food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed in the three stores ahead of the checkouts because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country the sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the revenues are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of appliances.
In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This year several thousand infections first caused by the misuse of antibiotics have been registered in hospitals.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the doctor-head of the department of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, an infection with MRSA was diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
In one man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital earlier in the year.
A person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon after had to return to the hospital as a result of the infection with MRSA and since then a major surgical intervention has not been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multidrug-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System - said Karolina B?r?cz, a doctor-head of the department of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections caused by multiresistant agents has certainly been recorded, of the rest there is no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria on their nose without causing any disease.
SA infections (e.g., throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once over- or over-applied to antibiotics, the bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics transform into highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and rapidly spread into inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, for example wound infections or septicaemia first to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened organism, to the elderly or to people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff treat them in rubber gloves and mask and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment" - said Tibor Nyulasi.
Inpatients are pre-screened for MRSA in their body, but infection cannot be prevented in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor for the prevention of formation and infection with multiresistant pathogens - says Karolina B?r?cz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should screen hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who have MRSA in their system.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when the visible MRSA infections in the patient already occur - said the doctor-head of the department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes stringent mandates for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina B?r?cz.
You save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however also in this regard considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is spread through droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital wards are often crowded, beds are often close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - added Karolina Borcz - that in the hospitals of less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater chance for infection.
In Karolina’s opinion, where the appropriate prevention measures are met, there are fewer infections of this type or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treating MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, which is why it is being fought in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The programme appears to be successful, according to data provided, with MRSA infections showing a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-drug resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative breathalyzer control of the police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report has been made on the case of the fatal accident caused by the commander of the XXII district police.
The possibility that he was driving drunk or in a dazed state can be excluded the since resigned commander of the police of the XXII district, who on Tuesday struck and caused the death of a passer-by - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Prosecutor General of the Capital, after having prepared the expert report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary alcohol control that had already found that the former police commander did not drink alcohol before getting behind the wheel.
The then-head of the XXII district police station on Tuesday in his private vehicle at the turn of Kossuth Lajos street in the XXII district ran over a 55-year-old man who was trying to cross the street, but not in the designated pedestrian zone.
(This last fact, that is, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not extenuating circumstances, the driver must always give way when bending.)
The bystander lost his life after being hospitalized.
