Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the beginning collaborated with the prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
400 million euros more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice-President Marta Gajecka signed three credit limit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total value of 400 million euros to finance education, transport and environment infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
In 2006 the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a budget of EUR 300 million to finance transport and environmental protection projects in the Hungarian budget, to be implemented from the grant of cohesion funds, of which the parties had already signed a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed relates to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The credit agreement of 150 million euros is also intended to finance the budget of educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of 300 million euros for this objective of Hungary, on the use of the remaining 150 million euros the decision will be taken later, by extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the innovation and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the issue of the construction of the 4th Metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalizes with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will return to the issue of whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do it.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on the claims is adjusted to EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging a fee for keeping the claim available to the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards that Balkan country just mentioned.
What, where and who buys from the EU market even cheaper, will it quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap ski apartments and beach chalets.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches of Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Costa del Sol", the old Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for real estate also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to the analysts of Re/Max in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy real estate in the especially cheap area of Rus.
The capital Sofia can also be attractive, with commercial and office spaces promising a quick return on investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, thus being a prominent destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already doing their shopping, for example in the surroundings of Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria also strive to change their lives and their way of life.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot promoters are also present and there are traditionally many Russian customers on the beaches of the Black Sea and in ski paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renew them later.
They require good communication and access, and for them the proximity of a large city, shops and usually a local doctor is important.
They constitute the second category of buyers of chalets (Bulgaria in the month of December was included among the top 10 holiday destinations of Germans).
The third group are real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital real estate is constantly growing, since the demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years they suffered an annual increase of 21 percent.
The increase in the price of real estate considerably outpaces the growth in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian Six Percent
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at the expert level will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration negotiations will continue at the ministerial level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and policymakers from 192 countries around the world discuss the Bali Roadmap on post-period emission reduction efforts under the Kyoto Protocol, which runs until 2012.
There are now lively discussions on the subject between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that at the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to agree that compared to the situation in 1990, until 2020 the emission of the gases responsible for the greenhouse effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological aid to countries in need.
Agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for under the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member Governing Council, likely within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac es Profit".
Six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020, regardless of whether or not the “post-2012 agreement” will be signed, and is willing to commit to reducing even 30 percent if the other large developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to a decrease of 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU Member States committed to comply with an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce by 6 percent the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect with respect to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will comply with - says the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
Much is at stake in Bali, since in two years time the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because otherwise, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emissions reduction, whose need was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the international scientific association of the UN that obtained the Nobel Prize.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and could not prevent an increase of more than 2°C in the average temperature of the Earth, a fact that according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army Recruits on YouTube
British army units at a video distributor post recordings about actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British air force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with helmet-mounted mini-cameras are monitored in Kandahar’s general operating body, then sent to London to be uploaded to the internet.
The political message is inevitable.
139 recordings have already been uploaded to the Internet and their “channel” has already been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defense headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions carried out in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Ministry of the Commonwealth of Nations (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the British army’s presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional TV recruitment spots - the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'etre of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans made a video game.
The army is also concerned by the fact that, in addition to the recalcitrantly edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the distributor, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without presenting however the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan have been uploaded to the Internet and numerous videos recorded in real operations, but the British army is only lately taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with the free-to-download shooting video games, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers.
