The forces of the giant strike are gathering
The League Trade Unions and the National Federation of Workers’ Commissions will set up a strike commission on Friday to coordinate Monday’s indefinite strike.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday, while on Monday - the day on which the final vote on the public health law will be held - a work stoppage will begin.
Surely this action will cause great difficulties in transport, since rail traffic will be completely stopped and until 1 p.m. the workers of the Collective Transport Company of Budapest will also be on strike.
On Friday afternoon the League Trade Unions will report on the details of their strike on Monday that they will hold jointly with the National Federation of Workers’ Commissions.
The strike committee of the LIGA and the National Union of Machinists will also be set up to coordinate the actions on Monday.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday, while on Monday the participating unions will strike indefinitely, if an agreement with the government is not reached.
This means that - on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law - they did not report on the date of the end of the strike started.
If the National Assembly disapproves of the public health law, the unions will immediately withdraw their call for a strike.
Instead, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on the future.
On the basis of the National Assembly’s Monday agenda, it is also possible that only the public health law will be voted on in the late hours of the night, or perhaps close to midnight.
As a result of the strike that will start on Monday, there will be significant difficulties in transport: on the railways you will stop working indefinitely, in the morning you may stop a part of the collective transport of Budapest and more than half of the intercity bus transport of the Volán companies.
At the same time, in many parts of the country there will be closure of half of the roads.
Numerous unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, their names are constantly updated on the League’s website.
Some unions announced their strike indefinitely, others for a defined time.
Until Thursday afternoon, the State Railway and the Free Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) could not reach an agreement even on the minimum services, although, as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are traveling on trains.
According to information received so far, from the start of the day until 1 p.m. will be on strike workers of the Collective Transport Company of Budapest, Budapest Airports from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m., hold a four-hour strike the Unions of LIGA of the Electrical Industry and Thermal Energy, the Unions of Educators called for a strike of 2 and the Democratic Union of Educators from 2 to 8 hours.
The Hungarian Medical Association will take part in a national strike at alternative times and the Democratic Union of Health and Social Sector Workers (SDTSSS), which are part of the Trade Union Cooperation Forum, will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is for the government to withdraw its proposal on public health reform and submit a new conception to a social debate.
The second demand is that they gradually introduce the new form of calculation of pensions that will come into force next year.
The third is that they ensure, even before 2010, in the case of advanced pensions, the possibility that the occupations that deserve it can enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Union of Railway Workers (SLTF), which is part of the League Unions, does not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway side lines and expects another different proposal.
Political Capital[b1]: The Hungarian Guard increases the risk in the country
According to the Risk Analysing Division of the Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed in August this year with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
In the company’s “risk warning” it is written: in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard the greatest political risk is constituted by the fact that “with the aggravation of the ethnic tensions existing between the Roma and non-Roma population of Hungary, even in the short term violent ethnic clashes may occur”.
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably the provocation of an event of this nature - added the representative of the research institute.
They stated that all this is due to one of the main faults of the protagonists of Hungarian political life: "the protagonists of public life gave the public debate of the Gypsy problem to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who were able to base their political strategy on the existing discrepancies between Gypsies and Hungarians".
This aggravates the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of the outbreak of violent conflicts.
In addition to this, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international average, "significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially as it relates to the stability and democratic development of the country."
They remind us that since the autumn of 2006 the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has received increasing publicity and momentum, and that since the summer of 2007 numerous organizations have formed in the country that define themselves as "national self-defence associations".
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil organizations, while openly proclaiming the training of their members for defense - even armed - (civil defense, national defense, defense of public order), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, of the army, that is, of the State," they add.
