A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Bad Arolsen Nazi archives, which describe the fates of 17.5 million Hitler regime victims, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were thus far not consultable only for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his successors.
The eleven States in charge of its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to seekers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to search “particularly on the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the state of health of forced labourers,” explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Red Cross Commission (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, were opposed to the opening to the public of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the supposed homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or of the detention orders established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the countrymen deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent wage earners deal with tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents," Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Centre on Antisemitism at the Technische Universitat in Berlin, had stated in 2006.
