The Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which entered into force 1 November
In parallel with its parliamentary process, which ended today with the vote by Congress on the amendments incorporated into the bill in the Senate, the Government has submitted to a public hearing the regulations that will develop the new law, with the objective that both enter into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the effort made by deputies and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulations in order to guarantee the protection of investors and regulate in detail the activity of the entities so that the markets work efficiently.
The Mifid, which modifies the Securities Market Law, involves the modernization of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the different supervisors of the European Union.
The new rules will allow financial advisory services to be provided to specialised firms as well as to natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFI), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of transactions in financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are added multilateral trading systems and systems of internalization of orders, which will compete with the current stock exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment firms to disclose information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and forms of risk management to the market and requires them to keep a record of all transactions they undertake, in order to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
In its passage through the Committee on Economics of the Congress, several modifications were incorporated, among which it stands out that the securitised debts are considered as a "complex" financial instrument given their high danger to the investor, which has been demonstrated with what happened with the debt of subprime mortgages.
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delimit the functions that graduates can perform in Economics and Business 30 years after the Royal Decree was approved in 1977 that delimits the professional functions reserved for economists.
