Venus may have once been a fitting place for life, scientists declared yesterday.
Data from an orbiting European spacecraft showed the planet more like an Earth twin than had previously been observed.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus into a very different kind of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is enough to melt lead and is eroded by hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The results from the European Space Agency's Venus Express, which has studied the planet for a year, offer an overview of how the Earth could develop catastrophic climate changes.
Professor Fred Taylor, from the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, when they are two such similar planets.
“Our new data make it possible to build a scenario in which Venus began as Earth, possibly with a habitable environment millions of years ago.”
