However, Republican presidential candidates eventually agree to hold a debate on YouTube, in which ordinary voters record questions on video and send them for dissemination among the candidates.
None of the questions posed on Wednesday afternoon were more ridiculous than the snow monkey that asked Democrats about climate warming in the YouTube Republican Party debate.
But the questions, and the answers, this time reflected much of the state of the Republican party ahead of next year’s election.
It’s not known exactly how CNN producers, who co-sponsor the debate, chose YouTube videos to show aspiring candidates.
But the first half-hour of debate, the longest devoted to a single topic, focused on immigration.
The issue is one of the most potent topics for Republicans.
CNN called on a group of undecided voters to step up the dial when they heard ideas they liked: Issuers noticed spikes in approval when candidates spoke with extremist arguments.
The toughest exchanges of words of the night were between Rudy Giuliani, the national pioneer, and Mr. Romney, who has been leading the way in crucial polls in Iowa and New Hampshire.
Mr. Giuliani is trying to ruin Romney’s reputation because he was soft on illegal immigration when he was mayor of New York.
He attacked Mr. Romney, accusing the former Massachusetts governor of hiring illegal immigrants to work at his home.
Both responded aggressively when asked if any candidate could support an “amnesty” (allowing illegals to regularize their situation and giving them the possibility of obtaining citizenship).
Minor candidates such as Duncan Hunter, a California congressman, and Tom Tancredo, a Colorado congressman, settled on the issue.
Neither has the word to be nominated candidate, but both remain in the race perhaps because they both raised the issue of immigration before the others.
At least in immigration, and broadly speaking, candidates share views: increased surveillance at the borders, intolerance of illegal immigrants.
This topic, along with China’s fear of toxic toys and other foreign concerns, helps Republicans forget, or minimize, divisions between liberals and Christian conservatives.
But the debate turned uncomfortable when other issues surfaced.
Giuliani was asked why he had supported gun control in the past.
John McCain and Mr. Romney debated whether immersion in water should be considered torture.
One person asked if the candidates believed every word of the Bible.
This led Mr. Giuliani to stumble into the position that while the Bible was his favorite book, he did not literally believe in the story of the Jonah and the whale.
Another person asked if Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee – now, against all expectations, first in Iowa’s most recent poll, thanks to his long-standing Christian conservatism – said the death penalty was painful but necessary.
When pressed to answer whether Jesus would be in favor, he laughed saying that Jesus was too smart to be a candidate in the election.
The race remains unusually open.
Mr. Huckabee is on the rise in Iowa, coinciding with liberal Ron Paul’s fundraising campaigns and his heated remarks from Wednesday’s debate.
The two have come out of the background, because the two wings of the party did not agree on the most famous and traditional candidate.
In 1980 and 2000, a candidate united the party early and convincingly with a winning message about the greatness of America, satisfying both wings of the party.
This time the match is divided and the result is far from clear.
Labour pains
Gordon Brown has discovered another hole to sink into; but still he emerges.
As political scandals continue in England, this one is not particularly interesting.
No influences seem to have been sold, no exorbitant hotel accounts in Paris, no sucking extramarital fingers.
But it has been revealed that a wealthy businessman has disguised contributions to the British Labour party of more than 650,000 pounds ($1.3 million) for about four years using fake names, and that the party did not denounce him.
Two months ago, when the prime minister shied away from calling for an election, stupidly insulting British intelligence by declaring that opinion polls did not influence his decision, the hope was that it would provide a strong and efficient government.
But instead, like Vince Calbe, the liberal Democrat leads with increasing ingenuity, because the dreaded Mr. Brown has gone from being Stalin to being Mr. Bean.
The bailout of Northern Rock, a troubled bank, demonstrated regulatory weakness and poor judgment in times of crisis.
Bad proposals to change the tax code have put business groups, together, against the government.
The tax authority lost 25 million personal data that revealed an unimaginable administrative botch.
A trio of retired generals started a mutiny in the House of Lords, protesting against cuts in military spending: being ministers of the armed forces is, they claimed, a part-time job.
Now it’s David Abrahams’ multiple donations; Peter Watt, the Labour general secretary (and former accomplice) has already resigned.
None of this means Mr. Brown irrevocably walks out.
Governments may reach a tipping point after they find themselves unable to govern.
People don’t believe them as politicians, but they usually suspend their disbelief when a new batch takes over.
Once it is clear that the prime minister cannot improve things, that he does not have much time left, that suspension is over: public officials begin to fail; cabinet ministers are exposed; the press seeks bad news; and the government is put on the defensive and does not focus.
In one part, Brown’s position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders he cannot defend himself by arguing that he is new.
Although he wanted to disown Tony Blair, he was his senior lieutenant.
The problems of Northern Rock and the authority registration tax are related to the decisions Brown made as chancellor of the treasury.
And even when it’s not directly involved in Blairish mishaps – or “partner cash,” the investigation of political party funding – voters can assume it is.
However, Mr. Brown’s situation is not as bad as it seems.
The plates are not as bad as the Tories want to show.
As in Mr. Bean, no one has died, nor been directly scammed.
And the remedy, though painful, is to give what Mr. Brown’s naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable and brutal government.
The new political donation scandal is a good example.
Mr. Abrahams, who compares his donations to charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
This may be so, but the decision is not made by him.
The laws against anonymity for big political contributors are clear and exist for one clear reason: the public has a right to know who is buying access to those in power.
Mr. Watt, who said he heard about Mr. Abraham’s deal, and that it wasn’t illegal, will obviously face Jon Mendlesohn, head of fundraising who was asked about the donations in October.
But Mr. Brown is not involved so far: there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these performances, though the bulk of the payments were made after he took control of the office in June.
So far, the prime minister has done half the job.
He has been quick to condemn his party for breaking the law, but he is diluted in decision-making by a family matter, a commission of inquiry into the matter – led, to a large extent, by a judge and a bishop.
In this case, the morals are not complicated.
If the law has been violated, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things that Mr. Brown must do, such as find a permanent and independent head for the Standards Commission in Public Life, as he has not had one for six months, and he must also push for genuine party funding reform.
This will require hard co-operative labour with the Tories, and perhaps a renunciation of the special financial situation with the unions – bitter measures for a partisan like Mr Brown.
But he must face some partisan facts.
Conservatives now have a good level of support in the polls; he has two years to win voters; and the only way he can move to victory is to act with impeccable probity and solid competition.
Sharks Cards
Is the subprime mortgage crisis infecting the American credit card market?
When there’s blood in the water, it’s only natural for a pair of dorsal fins to swim around excitedly.
Now that the American housing market is in crisis, predators have their sights set on the country’s credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate credit card losses could reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis spreads other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of contagion are already visible.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been written off or that are more than 30 days late respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 million charge on its U.S. consumer finance business, in part due to card borrowers’ weakness.
However, it is too early for panic.
Delinquency and delinquency are at low levels.
According to Moody’s, a rating agency, the third quarter crime rate of 3.89% was almost one percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the American bankruptcy law (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy applications, which in turn represent a large loss on credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore, delinquency) would be growing again, or it may happen that the conditions for borrowers were worsening.
The industry also reports strong payout rates, which show how much of its debts consumers pay each month.
And confidence in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty firm, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emission volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct infection channels of the crisis between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge credit card debts now that lenders are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more at the flow of liquidity than active securities, so falling prices don’t necessarily trigger a change in borrowers’ creditworthiness.
They can even work to get ahead of the emitters.
Incentives for consumers to continue amortizing the mortgage decrease if the properties are worth less than the value of the loan; and as a result, the payment of the card debt goes up in the priority list.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions that mortgage lenders face by changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That should in theory reduce the risk of a rapid asset price cut.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and reassess all the loans,” says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If home prices are lower and a credit crunch pushes America into recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a more severe future.
Those dorsal fins need to be monitored further.
British bankers found guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who went on trial for their responsibility in the frauds with the former head of Enron’s financial office, Andrew Fastow, were found guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew were originally found innocent of seven counts of fraud for colluding with Fastow in a secret financial operation in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of employees.
They were sent to trial in January.
But during the hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each was convicted of collusion in fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich Natwest, a unit of the Scottish PLC group at the Royal Bank, became notorious in Britain for extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, his case marks the loose end of an investigation launched after the 2001 Enron collapse.
Initially, the charges against the bankers were to have alerted Fastow in 2002 that he was the target of a government investigation into the fall of Enron.
The indictment against the bankers - dubbed the "NatWest Three" - alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to concoct a fraudulent scheme with Fastow and his former top aide, Michael Kopper.
Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron company controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of a myriad of frauds at Enron, which helped its spiraling bankruptcy.
In 2002, the bank valued the subsidiary’s interest at zero, but the three Britons knew it would appreciate upwards.
A company under Kopper’s control bought the subsidiary’s bank interest for $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for interest on the company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely represented Enron, as the energy company would pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its portions of the subsidiary.
But the 20 million remained in the hands of the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers charged $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others received about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow was convicted on two counts of conspiracy in the collapse of Enron.
The trio of Britons were arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a 6-year sentence in a Louisiana federal prison.
Kopper is serving a three-year, one-month sentence in Texarkana.
Each of the three British bankers must pay the $1 million they required to live in the United States while the trial was taking place.
Enron, one of the nation’s seven largest companies, declared bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks, could not hide the debt of millions or make its failing businesses seem successful.
The collapse lost thousands of jobs, more than 60 million in market values and more than two million in pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former chief executive Jeffrey Skilling were charged last year for their roles in the company’s collapse.
Skilling is serving a sentence of more than 24 years.
Lay’s conviction for conspiracy, fraud and other charges was suspended when he died of a heart attack last year.
Neither down nor out in Moscow
The price of a Gulfstream G550, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and enough fuel capacity to fly direct from Moscow to Los Angeles, starts at $54 million.
But this is a small expense for some of the rich Russians.
“It can accommodate up to 18 passengers,” says Dan Firer, Gulfstream’s representative.
“But no one asks for that seat model because it’s for private family flights or for company presidents.”
Mr. Firer was in charge of the Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaire’s Fair, a four-day consumer orgy held at an event center near the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, 200 other luxury suppliers had installed their exhibition stands, hoping to lure wealthy new Russians into everything from mahogany coffered yachts to diamond-encrusted car grills worth 50 cents.
Mr. Firer looks cautiously at a bright orange Porsche on the stand next door to him."
“It’s a beautiful car, but it’s nickel and kettle compared to us,” he said.
“After the United States, Russia is the second largest market for private jets.”
Fueled by the oil boom, the Russian capital resembles Dallas when it was in its heyday.
“We experienced the same thing in 1890, when some wealthy Americans came to meet in Europe, where they were seen as materialists,” says Marshall Goldman, senior professor at the Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies at Harvard University.
“Like the Saudis of the 1970s and the Japanese of the 1990s, the Russians are emerging as the world’s biggest consumers and spenders.”
The world’s most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share of the pie.
Elsewhere in Moscow, a conference on the luxury industry will be held this week with Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, the president of LVMH, to exchange ideas on how to sell luxury goods in markets like Russia.
(The conference is organized by the International Herald Tribune, owned by the New York Times company)
Russia has 53 billionaires making a total of $282 billion, according to the Forbes list of the richest people.
In addition, the second-degree rich include 103,000 Russian millionaires whose money reaches $670 billion, according to a study of the evolution of personal wealth in the former Soviet Union, written by economists at the Center for Economic and Financial Research, a local think-tank.
(The World Bank says that in 2005, 15.8 percent of Russians were below the subsistence level.)
“There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow – and that’s why we’re all here,” says Nicole Marais, sales and marketing representative for David Morris, the London jeweller.
She attends the fair for the first time alongside the brand’s Russian distributor, the Soho Jewelry group.
"Women are impeccably prepared and men are very worthy."
Visiting the fair on Sunday night, dressed in afternoon attire, two real estate agents, Evgenia Yumatova, 21, and Svetlana Turovtsova, 26, described their clients and themselves as millionaires.
“I was looking at the cars and I’m trying to decide between the Infiniti, the Mercedes and the Porsche,” said Yumatova, who reeled off the design suit she wore as a veteran red carpet dishing with Joan Rivers.
The fair aims to appeal to the new rich, the kind of buyers who would be willing to stay several hours in a warehouse that mixes brands from Cadillac Escalades, platinum pen cutters, ice creams from Movenpick, custom-made pool tables, apartments in Dubai and teddy bears from Gund.
The general public can buy 30-euro tickets ($44.57).
“The Russians are interested in learning which brand is the most expensive and the best,” said Mr. Gijrath, who sat patriotically at a stand of Delft royal Dutch porcelains, in front of a mural-sized reconstruction of a Rembrandt painting, made of hand-painted tiles.
“Of course, the Russians are more interested in bling-bling.
In fact, the vendors said that wealthy Russians with more track record (10 to 15 years, by Russian standards) have changed their tastes from flashy logos to limited-edition brands, which would not be exhibited at a trade show.
However, several thousand people: millionaires in cash, emissaries of millionaires or tourists, fill the corridors every day.
And some of them buy.
On the first night of the show last Thursday, Roman Ershov, managing director of the King Koil beds, said he sold two $70,000-a-piece mattress systems, made of silk, cashmere and cotton interwoven with gold threads.
Also on the first night, Mikhail Lyubiumov, sales manager for A1 Moto, a company that equips high-end cars with ad hoc alarm systems, said the company had sold the bright orange Porsche for $170,000 to a Russian millionaire.
Late Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a company that customizes luxury cars, said he had sold three chain bracelet-shaped car grilles, for Rolls Royce Phantom, for $55,000 each.
He showed the reporter a car wheel, designed for a Russian casino owner, with rays embedded in Swarovski-colored crystals, so that it resembled a roulette wheel.
The cost: $22,000 for four wheels.
"The Russian millionaire who wants ostrich leather wheels or a portrait of his wife made of zircon cubes, is not necessarily going to drive on those wheels," says Mr. Karapetian.
“He’s going to keep the car in his garage, along with 30 or 40 other cars.”
Even if many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian clarifies that the phrase “Russian millionaire” does not mean exclusivity, given the surge in real estate prices.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already a millionaire, at least on paper if you're not cash," he said.
“There are more of them than you think.”
Those who weren’t millionaires could at least pretend to be rich by the support of the Continental Alliance, a Russian asset management firm.
The company made four red telephone booths (British style) stuffed with stacks of counterfeit $1 million bills.
Azad Karryev, the company’s marketing manager, said his team had printed 500,000 counterfeit bills for the Millionaire’s Fair.
Visitors would stop to shake off stacks of money, asking their friends to snap pictures on their phones while resting on piles of money, or pocketing a couple of million.
“You see, in Moscow, everyone can feel like a millionaire,” Karryev says.
'Scratch' surgery could lead to death in New Jersey
It was the day before Thanksgiving when Ronald Livingston looked through the window of the “Slightly Healthier” restaurant and saw an ambulance climb up White Cape Cod, two doors down West Scott Avenue.
Suddenly, a police car appeared.
And then another.
“Then I saw the ambulance coming up,” Mr. Livingston, the restaurant’s supervisor, said Wednesday.
"That's when I knew someone had died."
Authorities learned the dead woman was Olga Arroyo, 41, assistant to the Newark police department director.
Now investigators are trying to determine whether she died from a procedure performed by an unauthorized plastic surgeon, who is not yet identified by police, but who works at the home of 212 West Scott Avenue.
Authorities have not yet determined what caused Ms. Arroyo's death, but they are waiting for the toxicology test, though the results won't be available for a few weeks, to help resolve the mysterious death that has the upper ranks of the Newark Police Department distraught.
Ms. Arroyo had been an aide to police director Garry F. McCarthy since September 2006, and her voice was familiar to many in the department.
“She was loyal, hardworking and tenacious,” Mr. McCarthy says of Arroyo in a phone interview Wednesday.
"She was my guardian."
She protected me.”
Mr. McCarthy said Arroyo was the wife of Jimmy Arroyo, a former Newark police officer who works for the Alcoholic Beverage Control Commission, and left behind two 14- and 11-year-old sons and a stepdaughter.
Eileen Walsh, spokeswoman for County Union Attorney Theodore J. Romankow, said detectives are trying to determine whether Ms. Arroyo died following an unauthorized surgical procedure.
"That's one of the possibilities," Walsh said.
"It's an ongoing investigation."
Authorities said the house arrived at about 3 p.m.
On November 21, they found Mrs. Arroyo on a couch.
She was pronounced dead on the spot.
More than a week has passed and authorities have said little about their investigation or about the owner of the house, named Flor Margarita Castro.
Mrs. Walsh could not say whether Mrs. Castro had been questioned by the authorities.
Investigators are trying to determine which part of the house was used as a medical consultation.
On Wednesday, no one responded to the door at Mrs. Castro’s home, where a withered rose bush sits at the front of the house, and a Dalmatian barks at the back.
A blue drum labeled "vanillin ethyl" - used as a substitute for vanilla in foods and perfumes - stood on the garage door, next to a door leading to the basement.
Two mountain bikes hang from hooks on one side.
Mr. McCarthy said that when she arrived in Newark after 25 years in the NYPD, Mrs. Arroyo was invaluable in helping to get to know the new island city and its rough political culture.
“She would say, ‘You have to watch with this or that one,’” he said.
“She was always here when I was, and also when I wasn’t.
It's embarrassing."
The Federal Reserve is expected to cut rates to raise the stock market.
Stocks jumped on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday after the market expected the federal reserve to ease credit conditions with interest rate cuts, which were augmented by soothing comments from the vice president of the U.S. central bank.
Stock markets loosened in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, number two of Ben Bernanke, president of the reserve, declared that policy makers must be “flexible and pragmatic” in responding to the continued strain of financial markets.
In a clear effort to calm markets amid growing credit-exchange samples, Mr Kohn said the recent turbulence was “partly reversed by the improvement in the market at the end of September and during October.”
If the upward trend persists, it would increase the possibility of additional adjustments in financial conditions for real estate and business, Kohn said.
The comments were taken by investors as a sign that the reserve is ready to inject fresh capital into U.S. markets and to make further interest rate cuts, to stabilize credit conditions.
The remarks also helped calm Wall Street amid bad news for the U.S. economy, as home sales hit the lowest record in October.
The fallout from the financial turmoil was accentuated by a notice from Bear Stearns, an investment bank that will cut 650 jobs, equivalent to 4% of its total workforce, in a global cost reduction to offset losses from its investments in U.S. sub-prime mortgages.
Only 20 of those positions are expected to enter London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose by 331 points, or 2.55%, to close at 13,289,40, while the broad S&P 500 index rose 2.65%.
In London, the FTSE 100 index rose 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, to 6,306.2, adding more than 39 billion pounds to the value of Britain’s top-tier companies.
Germany’s Dax index rose 2.6 percent, and France’s CAC40 was above 2.3 percent.
Earlier, the resurgence of credit stress in markets was highlighted after strong demand in a three-month fund auction by the European Central Bank, which considered those loans to European commercial banks at 4.7%, the highest rate since April 2001.
Pressure on the Bank of England to follow the Federal Reserve and ECB’s performance and inject extra funds into the stock markets in London, strained credit and rates on three-month “Libor” loans among British banks, marking the biggest rise since September, at 6.59%, after a steady rise since Nov. 12.
England takes the demands of Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara with trial
Here are two dilemmas, each as difficult as the other.
Who should hit No. 6 for England in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, none is less important in the face of the first test against Sri Lanka, who should make the decision?
The second question is relevant because David Graveney, the president of the team that is on loan - with that particular title at least, is here to help Peter Moores, the coach, and Michael Vaughan, the captain, to decide; and also because the desk of Hugh Morris, director of England, is beginning to be filled with offers to become a national selector, and if not, in a part time.
Whoever doesn’t get sixth will be unfortunate, but life is often unfair and so is sport.
It is not easy to throw away what one man does at the top of his profession, while another never goes beyond the lower level, sometimes for lack of luck rather than ability.
Not only in cricket the choice is difficult, as judgments are required that always end up being subjective.
Is it time for Bopara to get up?
Is it fair to Shah if he does?
The same question could be asked in another respect if, says John Edwards or “Tubby” Banerjee, two bright young executives with good grades and who know the business well, had been promoted to the board: there is only room for one of them.
Who should say what a good level is for a cricketer, unless they give him a chance to sink or swim to the next chance?
Figures naturally have a big influence on decisions, but they also have opportunities.
Within a team, a cricketer has to catch the eye of the captain while taking a wicket and a hitter to get chances to change the order if he wants to make an impact as a player one day.
But catching the eye of the selectors is more complicated.
There were many who improved last season, for example James Anderson, who plays surely in the first test even if Stephen Harmison declares for "fit and bowls" like the wind in the nets.
Anderson took 32 first-class wickets in 33 runs each to earn a place.
Chris Tremlett took just 29 on the same average, but both have had their highs and can expect more from these.
Shah’s or Bopara’s games at Asgiriya Stadium may only be a matter of opinion.
The choice can break or make a man’s career, or it can make a small difference.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played in every test and did well in the first, with 5 wickets and 40 useful runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, struggling to establish himself at the same time who went on to become a major player, and despite scoring a hundred double against Australia in Australia, he may still be underrated.
The likelihood is that Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, after further discussion in today’s session at Asgiriya Stadium, will follow their conservation instincts and favor Shah’s greater experience over young Bopara’s exuberance.
There are arguments for both.
In Shah’s favor is his brilliant and valuable early 88’s debut test in Bombay, 32 hundred first-class versus only 6 Bopara, who, at 22, is seven years younger, and has excellent record against spin bowling.
But Shah made only ten runs in his two at-bats in May against the West Indies in the test at Lords, his home as a Middlesex player, and that caused an immediate pushback from selectors when Vaughan claimed his place for the next match, he seemed to have taken from his "batting" something of élan than in Bombay.
By contrast, the Essex team has joy in living on swords.
He latches on for nothing on the cricket field and his attitude was summed up as when he overturned his vehicle at an exhibition for England’s car sponsor, Volkswagen.
He suffered minor injuries and presumably a shock, but the first thing he did was pull out his Vodafone (sponsored, of course) and call Alastair Cook, his teammate looking into the distance, to say excitedly, “Did you see that?”
Bopara is the best player, he is including his slippery pass to have effects on his plays that seem to satisfy him, because he bats with confidence and skill.
Choosing the right man is one thing, choosing the best time, another.
Perhaps that is the true art of selection.
My inclination would be to give Bopara his chance, which doesn’t mean that Shah doesn’t stand out, as tea leaves suggest, it’s him who plays here this weekend.
Buses bring refugees back to work – and to the fight against Al-Qaeda
The first buses with Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, expelling the exiles who ran out of cash, no visa extensions and those waiting for the city to return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the militants who drove them out of their homes.
At Mansour bus station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy composed of a dozen buses, the terminal was full of refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned by private transport.
“I decided to go to Syria after many doctors were killed in Baghdad,” says Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
“I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspapers, about what happened in Baghdad and it’s safe now.”
"They say Mahdi's army stopped killing people," he says, referring to the Shiite militia of religious militant Cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who ordered his troops to temporarily cease.
Qassim al-Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher in the Sunni area of Amariyah, returned with her two sons because it was impossible to renew her visa in Syria because the regime does not want Iraqis working in their country.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah called him on the phone to tell him that a U.S.-allied force helped pull al-Qaeda out of its stronghold west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of the newcomers from Jordan was the head of a Sunni and Shia tribe that had been driven from their home in Sleikh north of Baghdad by a grenade attack, after he urged citizens to rise up against Al-Qaeda.
He had come to fight.
“Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had started an anti-Al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my comrades.”
"That's why I'm back today," said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they have been drawn to the growing calm in the capital since U.S. troops entrenched groups of “concerned citizens,” armed and working in cooperation with the U.S. military to defend their neighborhoods.
But many said they had returned because of visa denials and a lack of money in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have settled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, 51, a father of three, gave voice to the common suspicion among exiles, that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, called on the Syrian government to impose restrictions on refugee visas to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people believe they have fled the country because of the sectarian death squads.
"We were fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and urged the government to stop granting visas to Iraqis, to force them to return to Iraq," the Sunni said.
“I can’t believe in a government that supports the criminals who set fire to my house after I left it.”
Part of the reason for the cessation of violence is that Sunnis have been driven out of Shia areas and vice versa, easing tension.
There is a fear that a sudden surge of refugees will re-emerge sectarian tensions and the struggle begins.
Little Sarre, good manners.
The smallest federal state is the first in vocational training and even shines by the international orientation of its high schools.
As in the whole country, the Sarlandians lack only one educational field.
"Yesterday I explained for the fiftieth time to a non-Sarlander that we are not French" - that was the ironic motorcycle upon themselves of the smallest federal state for its fiftieth anniversary.
At the same time France and Luxembourg have a large role in the educational system of the Saarland which in a study of the Institute of German Economics (IW) called "Bildungsmonitor" ranked fifth.
In this way, high schools by tradition have good relations with neighbouring countries.
The University of Saarbrucken was founded in 1948 by the French.
Until today students can finish their university degree here with two or three diplomas.
Consequently, the percentage of foreign students is high, at 15.6 per cent.
