Venus is the twin brother of Earth.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that until now had not been raised. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirlpools at the poles, the same that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers have suspected that lightning could exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays are silent from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to Urey-Miller’s famous origin-of-life model, lightning caused life on Earth: tempests may have triggered reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the building blocks of life.
On Venus it’s not like that: if there was ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface temperatures of 500 ° C reign, oscillating in such a way that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Venus is possibly a 'diabolical' twin of Earth, but it is still a twin," Russell said.
The main goal of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so Earth-like by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest research findings that will be presented in many Nature papers, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also shows that neighboring planets have more features in common with Earth than we had previously assumed,” reports ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers discovered in the south polar region also a vortex formed by the fastest rotating clouds.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric terrestrial layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet is also called the Dawn Star or Evening Star and orbits the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not closely resemble Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets water had agglomerated that on Earth stayed in the oceans, but on Venus it disassociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
